The Constitutione of Ingelram (or Ingeram Lindesay) Bishop of Aber- deen, in the year 1448, are followed by Rules entitled Ordinatio Obori, with minute directions for the stations or positions of the choir, and for the proper ritual observances in the cathedral church.³

The following important passage occurs among the Statutes confirmed by the Bishop, Dean and Chapter of Moray, in a convocation held in the cathedral church of Elgin in the month of July 1242 :--“ Item receptum est et approbatum communiter, ut in Divinis Officiis in psallendo, legendo, et cantando, ac aliis ad Divina spectantibUS, servetur Ordo qui in Ecclesia Salisbyryensi esse noscitur institutus.” ⁴
